item.description:
1. Use named element tags These tags are more descriptive than &lt;div&gt;.
&lt;header&gt; &lt;nav&gt;
&lt;main&gt; &lt;section&gt; &lt;article&gt; &lt;aside&gt; &lt;form&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;caption&gt; &lt;figure&gt; &lt;figcaption&gt;
&lt;footer&gt;
1a. Forms and Inputs If the element functions as a button, use &lt;button&gt; (as opposed to just &lt;a&gt; or &lt;div&gt;). Buttons have inbuilt keyboard controls for focusing, selecting and clicking.
&lt;label for=&quot;MYName&quot;&gt; to assign a label to the input with the same name: &lt;input name=&quot;MYName&quot;&gt;
1b. Keyboard Access tabIndex=&quot;0&quot; to make an element tabbable.
